  "Prerequisites": "Learners should have a basic understanding of how web applications work, including familiarity with APIs and HTTP requests, along with some experience using or integrating third-party services in a software project.",
  "Learning objectives": "By the end of this course, you will be able to identify common security vulnerabilities that arise when integrating external AI services into applications, and explain the potential risks these weaknesses pose to data privacy and system integrity. You will also be able to apply practical strategies to assess, mitigate, and manage those risks, helping you build more secure and resilient AI-powered integrations.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "lesson title": "Insecure AI API Integrations",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "When you connect an application to an external AI service, you introduce a range of security risks that are easy to overlook, especially if you are new to working with APIs. This lesson explores the most common vulnerabilities that arise from insecure AI API integrations, including exposed API keys, insufficient input validation, and overly permissive access controls. You will learn how sensitive data can be leaked or misused when integrations are not properly secured, and why these risks are particularly significant when AI services are involved. By the end of this lesson, you will have a clearer understanding of the practical steps you can take to protect your applications and the data they handle. No prior security expertise is required, just a willingness to think carefully about how your integrations are built and configured.",
      "status": "draft",
      "content": "Risks when connecting applications to external AI services.",
      "slides": [
